  "notes": "Key decisions and ambiguities:\n\n1. TICKET 014/023/030 (API rate limits): Classified as billing-other because the customer is on a documented plan limit (600 req/min on Business) and is requesting a contract modification (higher limit or burst allowance), not reporting a bug. The follow-ups (023, 030) are marked urgent because the customer explicitly references an upcoming quarterly review deadline and growing data backlog. Account IDs differ between 014 (MC-4221 implied) and 023/030 (MC-4221 stated), but the sender (ops@major-customer.com) and subject matter are identical — clearly the same issue.\n\n2. TICKET 007/011 (dashboard sharing): Two tickets from the same account (MC-3309) describing the same permission-denied issue from opposite sides. Ticket 007 is the original report; 011 is the duplicate from the sharer's perspective.\n\n3. TICKET 029 (extortion): Classified as spam-or-noise rather than security-incident because it is a classic extortion scam (BTC demand, 48-hour deadline, no responsible disclosure). A legitimate vuln disclosure would not demand payment. Recommend blocking the sender and ignoring.\n\n4. TICKET 022 (refund for downtime): Classified as billing-refund because the customer is explicitly asking for a credit/refund for a past outage. The outage itself is not ongoing (status page confirmed), so this is not incident-active.\n\n5. TICKET 016 (500 errors on exports): Classified as incident-active because the endpoint is actively failing (30% error rate) and the customer has a time-sensitive deadline (SOC1 review tomorrow). The status page showing green suggests this may be a partial outage not yet reflected there.\n\n6. TICKET 019 (GDPR request): Classified as legal-compliance with normal urgency. The 30-day statutory window provides time, but this should be routed to legal/compliance team promptly to avoid missing the deadline.\n\n7. TICKET 010 (podcast pitch) and TICKET 018 (acquisition inquiry): Both classified as external-business. These are not customer support tickets and should be routed to sales/leadership or dismissed.\n\nRecommended triage order (by urgency then category):\n  URGENT: 003 (login outage), 016 (API 500s), 028 (security compromise), 023/030 (rate limit escalation)\n  NORMAL: 001, 005, 006, 007, 008, 011, 013, 014, 019, 020, 022, 024, 026, 027\n  LOW: 002, 010, 012, 015, 017, 018, 025\n  N/A: 004, 009, 021, 029 (spam — archive/delete)"
